# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-functions
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] In computer programming, **event-driven programming** is a programming paradigm in which the flow of the program is determined by external events.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] User interface (UI) events from keyboards and mice, touchpads and touchscreens, and external sensor inputs are common cases.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] Events may also be programmatically generated, such as from messages from other programs, notifications from other threads, or other network events.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programming is the dominant paradigm used in graphical user interface (GUI) applications and network servers.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] In an event-driven application, there is generally an event loop that listens for events and then triggers a callback function when one of those events is detected.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programs can be written in any programming language, although the task is easier in languages that provide high-level abstractions.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] Although they do not exactly fit the event-driven model, interrupt handling and exception handling have many similarities.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] It is important to differentiate between event-driven and message-driven (aka queue-driven) paradigms: event-driven services (e.g.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] AWS SNS) are decoupled from their consumers, whereas message/queue-driven services (e.g.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] AWS SQS) are coupled with their consumers.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] Because the event loop that retrieves and dispatches events is common amongst applications, many programming frameworks provide an implementation of an event loop, and the application developer only needs to write the event handlers.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] The actual logic is contained in event handler routines.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] These routines handle the events to which the main program will respond.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] For example, a single mouse-click on a "Save" command button in a GUI program might trigger a routine to save data to a database.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] An "Exit" button might trigger a routine to exit the program.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] The event loop receives events from all such command buttons and other GUI elements, dispatching the appropriate event handler routine for each button.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] Event handler routines need to be bound to specific events, so the event loop can dispatch the correct routine in response to the event.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] Many IDEs simplify this process by providing the programmer with an event handling template for each specific event (such as a button click), allowing the programmer to focus on writing the event-handling code.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] In a sequential program, keeping track of execution order and history is normally trivial.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] But in an event-driven program, event handlers execute non-sequentially in response to external events.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] Special attention and planning is required to correctly structure the event handlers to work when called in any order.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] Most existing GUI architectures use event-driven programming.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] The Java AWT framework processes all UI changes on a single thread, called the Event dispatching thread.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] Similarly, all UI updates in the Java framework JavaFX occur on the JavaFX Application Thread.
[src:azure-functions/event-driven-programming] Most network servers and frameworks such as Node.js are also event-driven.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] Function as a Service is a subset of the serverless computing ecosystem.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] The "Grain of Sand Anti-pattern" refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] "Lambda Pinball" is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure Functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] Function as a service workloads may encounter migration obstacles due to service lock-in from tight vendor integrations.
[src:azure-functions/function-as-a-service] Hexagonal architecture can facilitate workload portability.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Azure was first introduced at the Professional Developers Conference (PDC) in October 2008 under the code name "Project Red Dog".
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] It was officially launched as Windows Azure in February 2010 and later renamed to Microsoft Azure on March 25, 2014.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure uses large-scale virtualization at Microsoft data centers worldwide and offers more than 600 services.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure offers a service level agreement (SLA) that guarantees 99.9% availability for applications and data hosted on its platform, subject to specific terms and conditions outlined in the SLA documentation.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] The Microsoft Azure Service Bus allows applications running on Azure premises or off-premises devices to communicate with Azure.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] This helps to build scalable and reliable applications in a service-oriented architecture (SOA).
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] A PaaS offering that can be used for encoding, content protection, streaming, or analytics.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Azure has a worldwide content delivery network (CDN) designed to efficiently deliver audio, video, applications, images, and other static files.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] It improves the performance of websites by caching static files closer to users, based on their geographic location.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Users can manage the network using a REST-based HTTP API.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Azure has 118 point-of-presence locations across 100 cities worldwide (also known as Edge locations) as of January 2023.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Through Azure Blockchain Workbench, Microsoft is providing the required infrastructure to set up a consortium network in multiple topologies using a variety of consensus mechanisms.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Microsoft provides integration from these blockchain platforms to other Microsoft services to streamline the development of distributed applications.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Microsoft supports many general-purpose blockchains, including Ethereum and Hyperledger Fabric and purpose-built blockchains like Corda.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Azure functions are used in serverless computing architectures, where subscribers can execute code as an event-driven Function-as-a-Service (FaaS) without managing the underlying server resources.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Customers using Azure functions are billed based on per-second resource consumption and executions.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Azure Local (previously Azure Stack HCI) is a hyper-converged infrastructure (HCI) product that uses validated hardware to run virtualized workloads on-premises to consolidate aging infrastructure and connect to Azure for cloud services.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Launched in September 2020, Azure Orbital lets private industries and government agencies process satellite data quickly by connecting directly to cloud computing networks.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Mobile cloud computing ground stations are also available to provide connectivity to remote locations without ground infrastructure.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Third-party satellite systems, like SpaceX's Starlink and SES' O3b constellation, can be employed.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] SES plans to use Microsoft's data centers to provide cloud connectivity to remote areas through its next generation O3b mPOWER MEO satellites alongside Microsoft's data centers.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] The company will deploy satellite control and uplink ground stations to achieve this.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] SES launched the first two O3b mPOWER satellites in December 2022; nine more are scheduled between 2023 and 2024.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] According to Microsoft, satellite cloud connectivity can provide lower latency than terrestrial fiber routes in specific regions.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] The company stated that during network testing for Xbox Cloud, satellite connections out-performed terrestrial networks in certain rural or geographically remote areas of the United States due to fewer network routing hops.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Azure Orbital was retired in December 2024, with existing assets being sold off to Space Leasing International.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] In August 2024, Azure launched Azure Container Storage, a platform-managed container-native storage service for the public cloud.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] The service supports Ephemeral Disks (Local NVMe/Temp SSD) and Azure Disks for containerized applications.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Azure Quantum provides access to quantum hardware and software.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] The platform provides access to third-party quantum systems utilizing varied hardware architectures, including trapped ion, neutral atom, and superconducting systems.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] In 2021, Microsoft developed the quantum programming language Q# (pronounced Q Sharp) and an open-source quantum development kit for algorithm development and simulation.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] In 2023, Microsoft developed Quantum Intermediate Representation (QIR) from LLVM as a common interface between programming languages and target quantum processors.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] The Azure Quantum Resource Estimator estimates the resources required to execute a given quantum algorithm on a fault-tolerant quantum computer.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] It can also show how future quantum computers will impact today's encryption algorithms.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] As of 2018, Azure was available in 54 regions, and Microsoft was the first primary cloud provider to establish facilities in Africa, with two regions in South Africa.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Azure geographies consist of multiple Azure Regions, like "North Europe" (located in Dublin, Ireland) and "West Europe" (located in Amsterdam, Netherlands).
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] On June 19, 2019, Microsoft announced the launch of two new cloud regions in the United Arab Emirates – Microsoft's first in the Middle East.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] On March 6, 2025, the company announced a strategic partnership with the Government of Kuwait, represented by the Central Agency for Information Technology (CAIT) and the Communication and Information Technology Regulatory Authority (CITRA).
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] This collaboration aims to accelerate digital transformation efforts aligned with Kuwait's Vision 2035.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] The partnership will focus on creating an AI-powered Azure Region to enhance local AI capabilities, stimulate economic growth, and drive innovation across various industries.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] In August 2018, Toyota Tsusho collaborated with Microsoft to deploy an aquaculture water management system using Azure IoT and machine learning applications.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Developed alongside researchers from Kindai University, the system uses computer vision on water pump conveyor belts to log fish counts, monitor stock quantities, and track automated water flow metrics via the Azure Machine Learning and Azure IoT Hub services.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure utilizes a specialized operating system with the same name to power its "fabric layer".
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] This cluster is hosted at Microsoft's data centers and is responsible for managing computing and storage resources and allocating them to applications running on the Microsoft Azure platform.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] It is a "cloud layer" built upon various Windows Server systems, including the customized Microsoft Azure Hypervisor, which is based on Windows Server 2008 and enables the virtualization of services.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] The Microsoft Azure Fabric Controller maintains the scalability and dependability of services and environments in the data center.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] It prevents failure in server malfunction and manages users' web applications, including memory allocation and load balancing.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Azure provides an API built on REST, HTTP, and XML that allows a developer to interact with the services offered by Microsoft Azure.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Microsoft also provides a client-side managed class library that encapsulates the functions of interacting with the services.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] It also integrates with Microsoft Visual Studio, Git, and Eclipse.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Users can manage Azure services in multiple ways, one of which is through the Web-based Azure Portal, which became generally available in December 2015.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Apart from accessing services via API, users can browse active resources, adjust settings, launch new resources, and view primary monitoring data of functional virtual machines and services using the portal.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Regarding cloud resources, Microsoft Azure offers two deployment models: the "classic" model and the Azure Resource Manager.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] In the classic model, each resource, like a virtual machine or SQL database, had to be managed separately, but in 2014, Azure introduced the Azure Resource Manager, which allows users to group related services.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] This update makes it easier and more efficient to deploy, manage, and monitor resources that work closely together.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] The classic model will eventually be phased out.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] In January 2025, Microsoft announced plans to invest $80 billion in AI and data centers as part of its fiscal year 2025 budget.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] This investment would enhance the scalability and performance of Azure's cloud infrastructure, which supports AI-driven applications, including services developed through Microsoft's partnership with OpenAI.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] In 2005, Microsoft took over Groove Networks, and Bill Gates made Groove's founder Ray Ozzie one of his 5 direct reports as one of 3 chief technology officers.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Ozzie met with Amitabh Srivastava, which let Srivastava change course.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] They convinced Dave Cutler to postpone his retirement, and their teams developed a cloud operating system.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] At fiscal year-end 2025, Microsoft reported that Azure surpassed US$75 billion in annual revenue and operated over 400 datacenters across 70 regions.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] According to the Patriot Act, Microsoft has acknowledged that the U.S. government can access data even if the hosting company is not American and the data is outside the U.S.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] To address concerns related to privacy and security, Microsoft has established the Microsoft Azure Trust Center.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure offers services that comply with multiple compliance programs, including ISO 27001:2005 and HIPAA.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] A comprehensive and up-to-date list of these services is available on the Microsoft Azure Trust Center Compliance page.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure received JAB Provisional Authority to Operate (P-ATO) from the U.S. government under the Federal Risk and Authorization Management Program (FedRAMP) guidelines.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] This program provides a standardized approach to security assessment, authorization, and continuous monitoring for cloud services used by the federal government.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] In 2025, an activist campaign named "No Azure for Apartheid" accused Microsoft of providing cloud and AI services to entities involved in Israeli policies within the Palestinian territories.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Campaign organizers argue that Azure's technology could enable surveillance and displacement, drawing parallels to historical corporate involvement in apartheid regimes.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Similar activism has targeted other technology companies, such as the No Tech for Apartheid movement directed at Google and Amazon, though critics state that Microsoft's specific government contracts and military partnerships draw heightened scrutiny.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Protesters have demanded transparency, ethical oversight, and the termination of contracts that they state facilitate human rights violations.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Microsoft has stated that its operations comply with international laws and regulations.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] The following is a list of Microsoft Azure outages and service disruptions.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] A large variety of Azure certifications can be attained, each requiring one or multiple successfully completed examinations.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Certification levels range from beginner, intermediate to expert.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure's services can have varied and complex pricing models.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] In August 2021, researchers from Wiz Research claimed to have discovered a vulnerability in the Azure Cosmos DB database, referred to as "ChaosDB." They claimed that they had gained complete unrestricted access to the accounts and databases of several thousand Microsoft Azure customers.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] In August 2021, Microsoft claimed they mitigated the vulnerability and no customer data was accessed.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] In September 2021, researchers from Palo Alto Networks claimed to discover a significant cross-account takeover vulnerability in Azure Container Instances, named "Azurescape".
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] According to Palo Alto Networks' researchers, this vulnerability is the first known instance that allows one user of a public cloud service to escape their environment and execute code on other users' environments within the same service.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] Although Microsoft quickly patched the issue, Palo Alto Networks advised Azure customers to revoke any privileged credentials deployed before August 31, 2021, as a precaution.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] In September 2021, Microsoft claimed they fixed the vulnerability.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] In September 2021, researchers from Wiz Research claimed they found four critical vulnerabilities in the Open Management Infrastructure (OMI), which is Azure's software agent deployed on a large portion of Linux VMs in Azure.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] The researchers named it "OMIGOD" and claimed that these vulnerabilities allowed for remote code execution within the Azure network and could escalate privileges to root.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] They claimed that the vulnerabilities affected various Azure services, including Azure Log Analytics, Azure Diagnostics, and Azure Security Center.
[src:azure-functions/microsoft-azure] In response, Microsoft announced that it had released fixes for the aforementioned vulnerabilities in September 2021.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:azure-functions/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
[src:azure-functions/webhook] In web development, a **webhook** is a method of augmenting or altering the behavior of a web page or web application with custom callbacks.
[src:azure-functions/webhook] These callbacks may be maintained, modified, and managed by third-party users who need not be affiliated with the originating website or application.
[src:azure-functions/webhook] In 2007, Jeff Lindsay coined the term *webhook* from the computer programming term *hook*.
[src:azure-functions/webhook] Webhooks are "user-defined HTTP callbacks".
[src:azure-functions/webhook] They are usually triggered by some event, such as pushing code to a repository, a purchase, a comment being posted to a blog and many more use cases.
[src:azure-functions/webhook] When that event occurs, the source site makes an HTTP request to the URL configured for the webhook.
[src:azure-functions/webhook] Users can configure them to cause events on one site to invoke behavior on another.
[src:azure-functions/webhook] Common uses are to trigger builds with continuous integration systems or to notify bug tracking systems.
[src:azure-functions/webhook] Because webhooks use HTTP, they can be integrated into web services without adding new infrastructure.
[src:azure-functions/webhook] When the client (the originating website or application) makes a webhook call to the third-party user's server, the incoming POST request should be authenticated to avoid a spoofing attack and its timestamp verified to avoid a replay attack.
[src:azure-functions/webhook] The sender may choose to keep a constant list of IP addresses from which requests will be sent.
[src:azure-functions/webhook] This is not a sufficient security measure on its own, but it is useful for when the receiving endpoint is behind a firewall or NAT.
